<br>
I know of a few websites already but I was wondering if there was something better out there. (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.japanese-online.com">www.japanese-online.com</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> for instance)<br>
<br>
I know hiragana and some katakana, and I was wondering how I could improve my reading and reading comprehension skills (especially) as well as the other areas of the Japanese language.<br>
<br>
Thanks in advance <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ujefm.showPublicProfile?language=EN>jefm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/9/02 9:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=925.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Serious self-study</span><hr size=1> introduction to moden japanese by osamu mizutani...<br>
you can get it at amazon or abebooks.com<br>
it's out of print...it was made in the 70's i think...<br>
so far it's what works best for me...rather than lame phrase books that you'll never remember it gives you a conversation and disects how it works...used with a good japanese dictionary you'll easily get through it...especially if already understand hirigana and katakana...it also gets you recognising common kanji...and has tapes (seperate) and other notes (seperate)...very good...<br>
it lets you learn at you're own pace...if you can't read japanese at the start that's ok...but you will by the end...it has prononciation drills (with the tapes)...and reading comprehension (just a block of japanese text that you've covered in previous chapters)...it's very deep and you spend a lot of time flipping back and forth and to the mini dictionary in the back...and if you want more info...to the net :-)<br>
I think the author is on a language commitee with the ministry of foreign affairs in Japan...so it's credible and it's published by the japan times....<br>
decent for conversational japanese...great for reading <p><pre>
