<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showMessage?topicID=814.topic">pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showMessage?topicID=814.topic</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
this post also has a direct link to used versions of this book/grammer notes on amazon.  <br>
<br>
I have also heard many good things about the &quot;Japanese for Busy People&quot; series.  As demondavies suggests, a high quality dictionary is a must, as is hiragana (no romaji!!).  An example would the Shogakukan Progressive Japanese-English Dictionary.  The standard Kanji dictionary is the New Nelson Japanese-English Character Dictionary, though you may break your back (and your wallet) buying these straight off.  Don't feel compelled to drop a fortune on dictionaries, good dictionaries (you'll need at least one japanese-english/english-japanese and one kanji dictionary) can be had for around $20 each.<br>
<br>
A final suggestion would be, if you cannot find a teacher (i.e through auditing classes at the local university/private tutor) to try and find a conversation partner.  Nothing improves your language faster than talking to a native speaker! <p><center><B> <I>Mamonaku. 11ban sen ni  Panda densha ga mairimasu.  <BR>Abunai desu kara, kiiro no sen no uchigawa made osagarikudasai.  </I> </B></center>
